My initial proof of concept of this work had the changes split up into a number of patches, which incrementally introduce each piece of functionality:

https://github.com/berrange/nova/commits/gurumed2

You've squished everything into one giant patch which is not at all desirable

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Structural_split_of_changes

Now the code you've ended up with is fairly different from my proof of concept, but I still think it could easily be split up into 5 or more patches.

There are no inline API doc comments at all in any of the code. Every class must be documented & at least the important methods should be documented.

There are no tests at all. This is a must fix. All classes must have test coverage."}]

commit_message:
Adds support for building generic reporting

Adds a framework for building a text, xml, and json
reports by creating models and generators to generate
those models, and then serializing them by attaching
and running views.  Included is code for generating
the Guru Meditation Reports like in
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GuruMeditationReport

Implements: bp guru-meditation-report
Fixes: bug #1189570
Change-Id: Ie0ab6aa66bafe017507083e024a328bc52ef8bb0

commit_message:
Proposing a change to remove user validation tests

As per discussions from bug
https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/999084 and
patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/27593/

am proposing a change to remove these tests since

1. Passwords are optional
2. No restriction on the length of the password
3. Since password checks are optional, it doesn't make sense to check
email format as well.
4. May be these checks should be in nova unit tests as and when a
consensus on these validation standards are met.

As of now, it doesn't make sense to have these tests in tempest.

Change-Id: I5ac3a1df2f7b0241a0077a252c240da361ed10d3

[{'created': '2013-07-02 01:25:44.000000000', 'message': 'Rework associations from vpc to quantum resources.

Metadata cannot be used to store the relationships between VPC

commit_message:
Rework associations from vpc to quantum resources.

Metadata cannot be used to store the relationships between VPC
resources and the underlying quantum resources, since this prevents
VPC or Subnet refs from being passed in as parameters.

This rework results in no state being stored in metadata. Route table
relationships are inferred from the template. An assumption is made that
the quantum router associatiated with the VPC will have the same name
as the quantum net. The easiest way of ensuring that is to creat the VPC
in a different Heat stack.

Fixes bug: #1165050
Fixes bug: #1165056
Fixes bug: #1166779
Fixes bug: #1166787

Change-Id: I6fb087bfc63ed13703089a16ed57858e6911b7d8

Talked to Avishay. Agree to have it fixed in the future release.'}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2013-05-21 10:53:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I am sorry, what type of live migration are we discussing? AFAIK, Cinder doesnt have live migration feature yet. And adding a flag in a backport looks a bit like a feature to me than a bugfix. I am happy to change my opinion if others think this patch follows OpenStack's guidelines for backporting a bugfix."}, {'account_id': 4355, 'date': '2013-05-21 11:48:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: No score

Hey Rushi, sorry it's not clearer.  This is a fix for VM live migration, not volume migration.  During VM migration, the volume is attached to both the source and target Nova hosts at the same time.  The driver returned an error because by default the volume should be mapped to only one host, unless the 'force' flag is added.  This is what the patch fixes - it checks if the error is due the volume already being mapped, and if so, adds the 'force' flag.  The config option is there to allow admins to disallow this behavior if they deem it to be dangerous (this is basically multi-attach, which not everyone likes to enable).

In summary, this is a fix to make VM live migration work, and adds no new features."}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2013-05-21 12:33:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Okay, thanks. I think I'll change my opinion -- it looks like it falls under the category of bugs."}, {'account_id': 4355, 'date': '2013-05-21 12:47:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-05-22 05:09:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2013-05-22 10:34:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

* why is this an issue only in a particular driver? Do all other storage arrays allow multihost by default?

* new config parameters are fine on stable if they preserve the current behaviour. In this case current behaviour is considered buggy and changed by default, but I'm not sure how is ensured that multihost attach is safe? Is there any locking preventing the same volume being used simultaneously from two nodes?
IMHO on stable we should be conservative and keep the current safer behaviour i.e. storwize_svc_multihostmap_enabled=False by default with an appropriate warning in the parameter description, so that users can change it but are also fully aware of the implications. It also requires an entry in the release notes."}, {'account_id': 4355, 'date': '2013-05-22 15:00:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

Alan,
Thanks for the review!  We actually had that flag set to False in a previous version of this patch, and somehow it got flipped - great catch!  You asked regarding the safety of multi-attach.  Nobody guarantees the safety.  In the case of live migration, we trust that the hypervisor will do proper synchronization so that there is no data corruption.

This is an issue for this driver because attaching to multiple hosts requires the "force" flag.  Other storage arrays may not - I honestly don't know.

We will have a new patch shortly with a different default value.  Also, which release notes are you referring too?

Thanks again!'}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2013-05-30 16:14:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> We will have a new patch shortly with a different default value.

Have you posted it? Note that EOD today starts freeze in preparation for 2013.1.2 release.

> Also, which release notes are you referring too?

stable release notes e.g. https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ReleaseNotes/2013.1.1
stable-maint team compiles them initially, but anyone can add to them (it's a wiki)"}, {'account_id': 1420, 'date': '2013-05-31 03:44:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

commit_message:
Port multinic extension to v3 API Part 1

This changeset only copies the v2 implementation file into the
appropriate v3 directory unchanged. The copy as-is will not be
loaded by either the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second
changeset will then make the changes required for it to work as a
v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension porting
easier as gerrit will display only what is actually changed for v3
rather than entirely new files

Change-Id: I216d35be6a90fc7d2bf0b2f2ab0211384eb0cbc1

Also I'm not sure that the changes to search and servers is the right thing to do. Perhaps I'm misunderstanding how they are meant to work, but I'm not convinced they are wrong as-is in V2. Might be worth separating theses changes out into a separate patch."}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2013-06-19 02:19:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Chris, actually I have some doubt too. But I still raise this up. Hope get some suggestion.

Let me explain more detail about why change this.

The search original works as:
/os-hypervisors/[filters]/search
This looks like doesn't follow REST principles.
(I read this: http://www.slideshare.net/apigee/restful-api-design-second-edition#btnNext)
So change it as:
/os-hypervisors/search?q=[filters]
I use the suggestion from http://www.slideshare.net/apigee/restful-api-design-second-edition#btnNext at 77 pages.

The servers orignal works as same:
/os-hypervisors/[filters]/servers
Then it returns all the servers that run on the matched hypervisors.

So I changed it as:
/os-hypervisors/[hypervisor id]/servers
It returns all the servers on the specific hypervisor.

So if we want to finish the same task as old api, we should do:
hypervisors = GET /os-hypervisors/search?q=[filters]
for hypervisor in hypervisors
    servers += GET /os-hypervisors/[hypervisor.id]/servers


There isn't any wrong in v2, just change the api follow REST principles.

Thanks, Alex"}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2013-06-19 02:23:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

And I can separate the change 'search' and 'servers' into different patches."}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2013-06-20 06:15:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-20 07:07:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

commit_message:
Use print_function

Python 3.x does not provide the print operator
anymore. Use the print function, which is available
via an extra import from __future__ for all Python
versions >= 2.6

Change-Id: Ief6b43e7862deb6d4c6401d530830fe59b89cd34

commit_message:
Fixup assert_has_keys.

This test helper had awkward code that didn't support users in
debugging tests, as it didn't report enough information. Additionally
some style issues were present, which I fixed up at the same time.

Fix bug 1195239.

Change-Id: If07e54ae0f2db1152dfea2012ff39b0291955dd7

commit_message:
engine : perform periodic tasks with stored stack_context

The metadata update needs to be performed with the stored stack_context,
not the admin_context, which contains no credentials to e.g authenticate
with nova

Fixes bug #1196618

Change-Id: I0451604535a731de5ad57d2d52cdf183e58cf7b0

I'm quite confused, maybe I've been too far out of the loop on this. Fn::ResourceFacade makes no sense to me. Why isn't the function Fn::GetStackAtt or something that will make sense to current users?"}, {'account_id': 7135, 'date': '2013-06-26 06:42:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The function name is a result of the discussion at the following ML,
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-June/010012.html
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-June/010781.html

In summary, stack doesn't have metadata, deletionpolicy, and updatepolicy attributes. We are introducing a way to let provider template access some "attributes" (not to be confused with the attributes accessed through Fn::GetAtt) of its parent resource. So it's named ResourceFacade.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-06-26 11:52:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-06-26 15:02:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(5 inline comments)

The changes look mostly good, but there are several things not tested, it'd be nice to improve the coverage. Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-06-26 17:33:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ok, so avoiding confusion with resource attributes is good. However, that still does not explain to users of Heat, who have never had "facades" what the heck a "facade" is.

This concept needs documentation. Before it is merged IMO.'}, {'account_id': 7135, 'date': '2013-06-27 12:24:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (4 inline comments)

commit_message:
Create stack in class setup, rather than instance.

The intent of creating the instance in a setup method
was so that the test methods could share a single instance to perform
their tests.

However, doing it in setUp() resulted in an instance per test method,
which is the opposite of the original intent.

Moving instance creation to the class setup means only one instance is
created.

Change-Id: Ie54573e7371e53a60350a3693a740ac56925b520

Add GitHub tarball and zipball support

pipe handing in sources. The changeset add it in and restructured.

I think you are merging two different concepts.

UUID tokens and PKI tokens both support the same formats:V2 and V3 APIs.  They are just the mechanism used to validate: online versus in-process.  PKI tokens fall back to UUID token behavior for online validation

SAML would be like a PKI token, in that it could be validated in process, and also should be validatable online.

So the supported formats should be "keystone-v2", "keystone-v3" and "SAML"  where the SAML format should probably be modified by something that binds it to the openstack APIs (roles and projects)

UUID tokens can be used to refer to a SAML document, just the middleware would have to be modified to handle it.'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2013-05-14 21:23:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Adam, I am not changing the token format or trying to support SAML. All I am doing is to make token operations "customizable" so that deployers have the flexibility to override the default behavior for things such as token caching strategy to improve performance, service catalog manipulations, customized token IDs to improve supportability, etc.

This is no different than the backend drivers.'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-05-14 22:44:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Ok, i like token object but it can be later. 

Regarding the subclassing, i was just thinking it's easier to know what is common between the UUID provider and the PKI provider if the common stuff is in a class and refinements in a UUID/PKI specific class. Inheriting another implementation makes it hard to know what is really shared vs simply inherited. I'm not sure on the policy here but you might be able to even put some of that into the token driver. 

Does token_format = 'PKI' have a real use any more? can it be deprecated in favour of having the token provider set to a pki provider?"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-06-06 17:48:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(11 inline comments)

Needs some restructuring of the code.   We currently have multiple endpoints for V2 and V3 tokens, but we allow each to handle tokens of the other format.  If we are to extend this pattern, this code needs to be able to support an arbitrary pipeline of token formats, not just the two V2/V3, then the manager needs to be able to handle having multiples registered. 

Try to avoid putting state into objects on a per-request basis if those objects are just helpers."}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2013-06-06 18:53:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: (12 inline comments)

Adam, not sure if I understand this statement

"We currently have multiple endpoints for V2 and V3 tokens, but we allow each to handle tokens of the other format."

V2 and V3 tokens can be intermix. This patch does not change that.

While I don't disagree with the usefulness of a token provider pipeline. It needs to be more carefully study. commit_message:
pluggable token management

blueprint pluggable-token-format
bug 1186061

Abstract token management backend to make token provider pluggable. It enables
deployers to customize token management to add their own capabilities.

This change also consolidates authenticate path to one. Internally, we
operate on V3 tokens. V3 to V2 token format translation will be done
by middleware.

Change-Id: Ib230d8f87b1490b099b993587f82a2c1d6160a99

commit_message:
Add a way to enable 3rd party repos for packages.

This should enable installation of percona-toolkit which is necessary
for gracefully cleaning out the token table until a suitable solution
can be found and implemented in keystone-manage.

Change-Id: I3207addc4d40b0bea4508cae70b0c60b822b509b

commit_message:
selinux sanity checks

Some checks for selinux to help find some common problems

If selinux is in enforcing mode, then output a warning.  This is
useful for diagnosing possible problems from the logs.

Check for probable installation in homedir and the boolean
httpd_read_user_content flag; if it is not set, then various commands
will hang as requests such as "nova x509-get-root-cert" are routed to
httpd which then can't access necessary files.

Change-Id: I6c635228875ca75e98e707cf8687d7e6d9f02a89

commit_message:
Fix swift-proxy-server to work with latest keystone

keystone.common.environment needs to be initialized inorder
to work correctly. See corresponding bug for stack trace.

This is stopping me from setting up a devstack instance. This patch
gets me around my problem but I am not sure if it is the best way
to solve this problem. Maybe someone can take a look.

Change-Id: I38f0c26f98045dcbed6531f3ee23ccb0a367e481
Fixes: bug 1193112

subject: Only get source if target directory doesn't exist.
messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- http://logs.openstack.org/33964/1/check/gate-diskimage-builder-pep8/602 : SUCCESS in 7s
- http://logs.openstack.org/33964/1/check/gate-diskimage-builder-python26/595 : SUCCESS in 46s
- http://logs.openstack.org/33964/1/check/gate-diskimage-builder-python27/596 : SUCCESS in 24s
'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So taking keystone as an example the two elements that include the same source are keystone and openstack-db, would it be reasonable to remove the retrieval of the source from openstack-db? looks to me like if this is done we could remove the openstack-db element altogether (the only other thing it does it change the address mysql binds to), I'll give it a go and see if it works."}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Just as some extra info, this is currently happening in 5 elements while building a bootstack image

http://paste.openstack.org/show/39105/

none of them specify a particular commit/branch so I think this change is ok (for these elements at least), If this behaviour is acceptable then maybe I should spell it out in the README so its clear what the behaviour is.'}, {'account_id': 6449, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'd like to get some opinions from other folks on this.

My feeling was that having the build explode if there were clashing target directories, was probably a good thing. It quickly and clearly identifies a namespace conflict.

If we try to reuse something that already exists, we run the risk of silently introducing errors where someone was expecting an element to fetch a different branch, or even a different repo entirely and will not discover it until later in the build, or worse, at runtime.

Part of me likes the re-use though, so I wonder if we could cheaply test if the pre-existing directory is exactly the same repo that we are about to construct and error out otherwise. This still worries me a little because we can't predict what a given future element will do to mangle/patch/etc a repository it checks out."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm not sure what you mean by "5 elements are doing this".. what is 'this' exactly.

Anyway, I want it to explode, loudly and clearly, if two things try to put a git repo in the same dir. This is what element-deps is for. If they are accidentally conflicting, then that should _explode_. If they are meant to share the same common code, put that in an element and both depend on it.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes that sounds like a more sane approach. In many of the other cases, the lone project name means "the software" and the components mean "the init scripts to run it". keystone is unique in that it has no separation between, say 'keystone' and 'keystone-api'. But nova is depended on by nova-compute and nova-api. Quantum has a similar pattern.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Only get source if target directory doesn't exist.

Some elements use the same directory for their source code, if used
together they need to share the same git clone

Change-Id: Id87b246e75e9c3d3c741655bfa06383f7d22b94c

commit_message:
fix the wrong return code and exceptions in agent api

this fix the wrong return code in agent delete api,
and change exception from the HTTPUnprocessableEntity
to HTTPBadRequest.

this also remove the exception the HTTPServerError in
agent create, as it won't raise exception in db.agent_build_create.

Partially implements: blueprint v3-api-return-codes

Change-Id: I783da45bfb83b47116ec2d568470867cbd363ff0

commit_message:
Port extended-server-attributes into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. The copy as-is will not be loaded by either
the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second changeset will then make
the changes required for it to work as a v3 extension.

This is being tried in order to make reviewing of extension
porting easier as gerrit will display only what is actually
changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements: bp v3-api-extension-versioning

Change-Id: Idc9eed087a82f897d504a5c79e520883e537d060

commit_message:
Port extended status extension to v3 API Part 1

This changeset only copies the v2 implementation file into the
appropriate v3 directory unchanged. The copy as-is will not be
loaded by either the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second
changeset will then make the changes required for it to work as a
v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension porting
easier as gerrit will display only what is actually changed for v3
rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Ia5b80b70a7a459bf973de1c1aea8dc650e763b8d

Port Simple_tenant_usage API to v3 Part 2

This patch contains the changes required to adapt the Simple_tenant_usage
extension and the corresponding unittest to the v3 framework

Partially implements: bp v3-api-extension-versioning

commit_message:
port Simple_tenant_usage  API into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. The copy as-is will not be loaded by either
the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second changeset will then
make the changes required for it to work as a v3 extension.

This is being tried in order to make reviewing of extension
porting easier as gerrit will display only what is actually
changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements: bp v3-api-extension-versioning

Change-Id: I1618987cc905a6734b409eb9a7fe37c65b6aac28

commit_message:
Port scheduler hints extension to v3 API Part 1

This changeset only copies the v2 files (implementation and test)
into the appropriate v3 directories unchanged. The copy as-is
will not be loaded by either the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The
second changeset will then make the changes required for it to
work as a v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension porting
easier as gerrit will display only what is actually changed for v3
rather than entirely new files

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I992b8ee243f8ccc436f4a995c34d8b8e97ff7fa9

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-06-13 04:01:21.000000000', 'message': 'Port config_drive API to v3 Part 2

Ports the config_drive extensions and the corresponding unittests
to the v3 framework. Moves the commented out tests from the v3
version of test_servers to the config drive extension unittests.

Adds entrypoint infrastructure to allow extensions to extend the way
that the servers extension performs xml deserialization so extension
specific deserialization does not require changes to the core servers
extension. The blacklist/whitelist settings for extensions generally
also apply to server extension point loading.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Ic8b75cc8b353a6e22cbaf354317a78c4df8d937e

commit_message:
Port config_drive API to v3 Part 2

Ports the config_drive extensions and the corresponding unittests
to the v3 framework. Moves the commented out tests from the v3
version of test_servers to the config drive extension unittests.

Adds entrypoint infrastructure to allow extensions to extend the way
that the servers extension performs xml deserialization so extension
specific deserialization does not require changes to the core servers
extension. The blacklist/whitelist settings for extensions generally
also apply to server extension point loading.

Also merges in updates to config drive functionality which were applied
to the v2 API while this changeset has been in review

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/31314

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Ic8b75cc8b353a6e22cbaf354317a78c4df8d937e

commit_message:
Port config drive API to v3 Part 1

This changeset only copies the v2 files (implementation and test)
into the appropriate v3 directories unchanged. The copy as-is
will not be loaded by either the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The
second changeset will then make the changes required for it to
work as a v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension porting
easier as gerrit will display only what is actually changed for v3
rather than entirely new files

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I9a4b31ef06bbf05c25b4a5e96f5cee2ce4d80d2f

commit_message:
Port hypervisor API into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. The copy as-is will not be loaded by either
the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second changeset will then
make the changes required for it to work as a v3 extension.

This is being tried in order to make reviewing of extension
porting easier as gerrit will display only what is actually
changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements: bp v3-api-extension-versioning

Change-Id: I251dc18dda9756574c308a08423fd805a3e91182

commit_message:
Moved clustering setup to an attribute

Clustering is set to false by default.  When enabled, will setup
rabbitmq disk node clustering.  Also, added opscode to attribution,
somehow had removed them in the previous rebase.

Change-Id: Idd249d0d950f5f4eb44cd7c10566ece254ed7f45

commit_message:
Port fping extension to v3 API Part 1

This changeset only copies the v2 files (implementation and test)
into the appropriate v3 directories unchanged. The copy as-is
will not be loaded by either the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The
second changeset will then make the changes required for it to
work as a v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension porting
easier as gerrit will display only what is actually changed for v3
rather than entirely new files

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I55d15ab5f9f59a83dc67bac2d2f41ceee06085d5

commit_message:
Port coverage API into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. The copy as-is will not be loaded by either
the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second changeset will then
make the changes required for it to work as a v3 extension.

This is being tried in order to make reviewing of extension
porting easier as gerrit will display only what is actually
changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements bp v3-api-extension-versioning

Change-Id: I50ba45357378311d7bccb71f851e9e2915fc763b

commit_message:
port Host API into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. The copy as-is will not be loaded by either
the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second changeset will then
make the changes required for it to work as a v3 extension.

This is being tried in order to make reviewing of extension
porting easier as gerrit will display only what is actually
changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements: bp v3-api-extension-versioning

Change-Id: I7dd63b9952c10778427e7e0b0dd74f57cb4282ee

Bug # 1197054 - Added new official fedora cloud image link.

Fedora now includes 'official' cloud images, rather than the
unofficial ones provided in earlier releases. As such I have
updated the relevant paragraph to link to these.

commit_message:
Make test_deferred_delete() more sensitive.

Integrated test test_deferred_delete() fails many times. The logs show
that periodic tasks were all right, because report_driver_status() works well.
The only strange thing was that reclamation did happened.
Maybe reclaim_instance_interval is not short enough, which make the
soft deleted instance not old enough to be reclaimed.
So set a shorter reclaim_instance_interval to fix it.

Fix bug: #1193167,1193543

Change-Id: I198e2a86fc4e220d77e361102d3f1ca5f7feecd5

commit_message:
Enforce block device mapping reservations within the database.

Previously, the compute manager was utilized to single-thread
reservations.  This could result in an incorrect database state
if compute was unavailable when attempting to attach a volume.
The database now enforces the unique constraint within the API
layer to remove the necessity for performing the reservation
within the compute manager.

blueprint db-enforce-unique-keys
Fixes: bug #1180040
Change-Id: I593d78e793f42173411ec3997bab8f2e36a00c4c

commit_message:
Add element to install Openstack python-* clients.

There was no way to install openstack clients without installing boot-stack.
Elements like nagios need the clients but may be running on different nodes
other then then OpenStack control plane so should not install boot-stack.

Python-mysqldb was being installed twice, which is untidy and may slow things
down with some package managers.

Change-Id: Iaeecf88d781eb7adc4a903b8332e1a92eea5fe38
Authored-by: Chris Krelle <nobodycam@gmail.com>

We shouldn't be stubbing out the backend db implementation, and instead
be stubbing out the db.api itself. One small step in making us less
sqlalchemy dependant.

commit_message:
Make db.fakes stub out API not sqlalchemy

We shouldn't be stubbing out the backend db implementation, and instead
be stubbing out the db.api itself. One small step in making us less
sqlalchemy dependant.

Change-Id: Ifb2c45353edc281456e7407dd36b4cc4feea1ac0

commit_message:
Add unique constraint for security groups

- Add unique constraint (project_id, name, deleted)
  for security_groups
- Define new SecurityGroupExists exception
- Drop security_group_exists() in favor of catching
  SecurityGroupExists exception for security_group_create()

Fixes bug #1093458

Blueprint: db-enforce-unique-keys

Change-Id: Id9a1427587cc9250942d0abd9eafc69861352d9b

- Secgroup get also show its corresponding instance

Fixes bug 1190410

commit_message:
Port server password extension to v3 API Part 1

This changeset only copies the v2 implementation file into the
appropriate v3 directory unchanged. The copy as-is will not be
loaded by either the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second
changeset will then make the changes required for it to work as a
v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension porting
easier as gerrit will display only what is actually changed for v3
rather than entirely new files

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I8be578ed4fada25ec4a8aa8adb3addb0a3791f85

commit_message:
docfix apache2 now supports client chunked encodin

As reported in the documentation bug, the apache deployment guide's
reference to apache2 mod_wsgi not supporting client chunked encoding
has become outdated. It now supports this feature, using an optional
parameter.

Updated the paragraph in question to reflect this

patchset 2 mentions the WSGIChunkedRequest variable and adds it
to the sample configs - On by default. Feedback welcome

fixes bug 1194935

Change-Id: I07c5c8506ac34e1e0e08fa6d961babde2f9b7367

commit_message:
python3: Compatibility for iteritems differences

In python3 dict.iteritems(), dict.iterkeys(), and
dict.itervalues() are no longer supported. So use
six.iteritems() where it is appropriate.

Change-Id: I8b07dc2a89d790ec275d45f859e1644e9b00c837
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Don't error if no route

Grep exits with an error if no matches are found. Causing
firstboot to fail on seed VM's.

Change-Id: Ia75a70b86d569c3523773309c06ea54f6f2ab02b

Howdy angus.

I'm fine with leaving it. I just wanted to make sure its useful :-)

Also I've started expanding some of the explanations around the different patterns. 

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/TaskFlow#Activation_patterns

It'd be interested in hearing what u think about the **kwargs automatic dependency 'finding'. Is that useful or actually more painful. I have some ideas if its to painful/restricting that might make it easier (but then hooking up generic functions to taskflow would become harder).

For example the 'concurrence' library uses a concept of a mailbox that 'tasks' can read/write from (with basic matching). This could be another way to get inputs into tasks, although its much more intrusive (since it forces u to use the mailbox concept).

I was also thinking that it would be pretty useful to allow developers to connect the dependencies themselves (with or without the kwargs edge inference). This would make it easier to add a task dependency but not care about kwargs automatic filling."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-07-02 13:58:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Cleaning up various components.

1. In order to aid future features its useful to split
split apart the linear_flow and have a good base
class that is not connected to a ordered or linear flow.
2. Have the graph flow inherit from the linear flow since
it is performing a linear run using a topological ordering
of the tasks.

Change-Id: I287cd4a666caf09ca3a4cdf1d53814e9c6feb765

commit_message:
port Attach_interface API into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. The copy as-is will not be loaded by either
the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second changeset will then
make the changes required for it to work as a v3 extension.

This is being tried in order to make reviewing of extension
porting easier as gerrit will display only what is actually
changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Change-Id: I83803ed04f39cb7dda537d08d34e78a04cd64d4c

commit_message:
Add HACKING check for db session param

Add a HACKING check to enforce that public db/api and db/sqlalchemy/api
methods to not accept a 'session' parameter.

This check is initially disabled, since it is failing ~24 times right
now, but will be enabled once bp/db-session-cleanup is complete.

Change-Id: Ib89eea58555032dd142d4e21e62d66e2726f0d06

commit_message:
Adding host attaching support to Cinder

Changing 'os-attach' API interface to allow client mark a volume as be
attached to a host.

Implement bp: volume-host-attaching
docimpact

commit_message:
Remove junk file when ftp transfer failure

During spawn with powervm driver, the image transfer to the IVM host
may fail in some conditions, eg. IVM host doesn't have enough disk
space. It leaves the junk file in IVM host, and this will disturb
next spawn after resolving environment issue, need clean it.

Fixes bug #1188884

Change-Id: I7b8d719995c2702c89cf55cef5f34bde9d01c1b9

[{'created': '2013-07-02 18:39:43.000000000', 'message': 'Make test_deferred_delete() be deterministic

This makes the test_deferred_delete test deterministic in its
execution. Since it depends on periodic task scheduling and
a somewhat unknown amount of time before the state change
polling loop will give up, it has been failing a lot lately.

This enforces a run of the specific task needed, as well as
ensures that time appears to have elapsed sufficiently to
justify a reclaim.

Fixes bug 1193167

Change-Id: Ideaf8abd19b10e018d284085309fe63282fa4b82
'}]
commit_message:
Make test_deferred_delete() be deterministic

This makes the test_deferred_delete test deterministic in its
execution. Since it depends on periodic task scheduling and
a somewhat unknown amount of time before the state change
polling loop will give up, it has been failing a lot lately.

This enforces a run of the specific task needed, as well as
ensures that time appears to have elapsed sufficiently to
justify a reclaim.

Fixes bug 1193167

Change-Id: Ideaf8abd19b10e018d284085309fe63282fa4b82

commit_message:
Fix the filtered characters list from console-log

In fffcaea1 ^M was added to the list of characters to filter from the
console-log output but, because of a typo in the regexp, the
character '-' was added to that list too and has been removed since
then.

Fixes bug #1194032

Change-Id: Ia02b0b4c7027cbd09a51042ca1b5d28890413626

commit_message:
Enable Ceilometer to support mongodb replication set

At present, ceilometer does not support mongodb replication set.
As a result, when the primary mongod node is down, ceilometer can
not write or read meters.

Use pymongo.Connection object's replicaSet param and allowing to connect
with a host seed list will let the mongodb connection support replication set.

Change-Id: I8404ca5b08b6e73366161c07b3815f75bed7e0eb
Fixes: Bug 1188649

commit_message:
Skip security group code when there is no network.

This patch adds a simple check to the nova/quantum API that immediately
returns an empty list if there are no configured networks available.

Fixes bug 1191044

Change-Id: I34ac4dd56c71f99c7ed9ff632d6dc7036d91008d
(cherry picked from commit 8f3b3db9b04bb5ff7b9486dc6fc211745b983855)

commit_message:
Silence exceptions from qpid connection.close() (from oslo)

This is commit 15d8d698b7 in oslo-incubator.

Fixes bug 1185465

Don't log exceptions that happen during connection.close().  They're
not surprising (a closed socket can't be read or written), don't
require sysadmin attention, and provide red herrings in the logs
to distract from finding real root causes of problems.

Change-Id: Ia0e25fbc11094b5ad5d6d2cf7d0e786acb3df1f6
(cherry picked from commit 361d116d820939207a0b01399c3ce50c7bc30dcd)

commit_message:
Handle ECONNREFUSED exception in SolidFire driver.

The SolidFire driver wasn't handling connection exceptions
during init (capacity updates from scheduler).

This patch add a try/except wrap around the two places
that this is called and logs and error rather than crashing
cinder-volume service.

Fixes bug: 1195910

Change-Id: I30347cc0973bbf9dbc30ea02e204560095fc75b4
(cherry picked from commit d596bfe6562307343858f419062756640000b0c8)

commit_message:
Regenerate missing resized backing files

Fixes bug 1185588 (for stable/grizzly)

The only way to reliably determine whether we are using a legacy
(pre-Grizzly) backing structure is to look at the backing file
reference for the instance/disk itself. Thus, if we determine the
backing file contains an underscore, we use the value following it
as our legacy_backing_size, which is then used to create the
necessary backing file.

Change-Id: I145f71068c972a604e5361ae79d6315286136786
Cherry-Pick: 6e768363450774cfee90e41aa5c40af780d3e04a

[{'created': '2013-06-27 05:08:44.000000000', 'message': "Fixes for quota_sets v3 extension

Various fixes for the quota_sets v3 extension:

* Removes reference to ext_mgr as this is a v2 concept and causes
  the extension to fail to load

* Merges os-extended-quotas extension which was just used as a switch
  by it being loaded or not and didn't contain any content itself. The
  extension presumes the functionality is always enabled. This means
  that the force paramter must now always be passed if the client
  wants to set the new quota lower than what is already used and
  reserved

* Updates test suite and consolidates tests given extended quotas is
  no longer a separate extension

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I868636b526a5990f96e63168d50c2d894ed33d52
"}]
commit_message:
Fixes for quota_sets v3 extension

Various fixes for the quota_sets v3 extension:

* Removes reference to ext_mgr as this is a v2 concept and causes
  the extension to fail to load

* Merges os-extended-quotas extension which was just used as a switch
  by it being loaded or not and didn't contain any content itself. The
  extension presumes the functionality is always enabled. This means
  that the force paramter must now always be passed if the client
  wants to set the new quota lower than what is already used and
  reserved

* Updates test suite and consolidates tests given extended quotas is
  no longer a separate extension

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I868636b526a5990f96e63168d50c2d894ed33d52

I agree with Dan, a 4.6k line patch-set is much to big. I would prefer to see this broken into several patch-sets


" Big landings are more risky per line of diff than small ones due to reviewer cognitive overhead - reviewers get non-linearly less effective the larger the review." Robert Collins
See http://markmail.org/message/k6lnxurtiayqn5vx'}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2013-05-29 05:25:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

Our situation is:
The first time we attempt to submit the implementation of zvm driver, we have a minimum set of driver methods to make it works with nova and some functions to deal with xCAT call and xCAT response data. Its about 1300 lines(including some ut) at that time.
But we were told we should have spawn in our first commit. Then we add spawn and snapshot. Spawn and snapshot also require us to have corresponding code to manage image repository at xCAT side, attach volume and setup network in xCAT and z/VM... then the commit size goes to nearly 5k ...

So it seem not easy to break up commit to smaller commits that less than 500 lines, if we want to submit a zvm driver that can work end to end.

Does anyone has suggestions on how to break up the commit? Or any other suggestions to help it pass the review? Thanks in advance!'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-05-29 10:02:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

Huang, you can propose several dependent patches at the same time.  Each one being fully functional (not breaking tests etc).

SO the first commit can be the framework, the second can be spawn, the third can be snapshot.  This way a reviewer can review each aspect in isolation, and see how everything is fits together overall.

to submit several dependent patches, just create local branch with several patches and do a git review.'}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2013-06-04 09:37:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18.'}, {'account_id': 5930, 'date': '2013-06-04 09:40:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

commit_message:
Start to add OpenStack z/VM support

This is the first part of z/VM driver - the framework of z/VM
driver. Including:
 - driver.py, implementation of virt driver
 - instance.py, z/VM driver operates z/VM instance through it
 - imageop.py, handles image related operations
 - networkop.py, handles network related operations
 - volumeop.py, handles volume related operations
 - configdrive.py, z/VM specific config drive builder
 - utils.py, utilities for z/VM driver
 - const.py, defines constants for z/VM driver
 - exception.py, defines exceptions for z/VM driver

Part 1 of blueprint zvm-plugin

Change-Id: Ie20614e5df89651f05af688439a00d5b6055e66c

commit_message:
Increasing th backing volume size to 24GiB for parallel tests

The tempest parallel run will cause, more volume allocation at the same time.

The cinder lvm driver uses sparse file for storing the volumes,
so the 24GiB will not be really used, and the allocation time is almost
the same as for 10GiB.

The gate vm normally has enough free space for 24GiB loopback
volume files.

Change-Id: I287536c731f941293bf31d0befca3a65f8fa609f

commit_message:
Add support for storing volumes on GPFS

Key functions include efficient creation of snapshots and clones using
file system level copy-on-write mechanism. Copying of image blocks is
also avoided in case Glance backend repository happens to be on GPFS.

Change-Id: I851f589894b20f6d8a5f913687b09a4cd79df40a
Implements: blueprint gpfs-volume-driver

commit_message:
Migrate routes onto $EXTERNAL_BRIDGE.

Since we migrate IP addresses from $PHYSICAL_INTERFACE to
$EXTERNAL_BRIDGE this breaks routes - we need to migrate them as well.

Change-Id: I618fbe76d189cd5a79e12a5264a3fc9779b2483c

commit_message:
Move more baremetal items out of nova-compute.

Baremetal DNSMasq and the baremetal deploy helper are not relevant to
nova-kvm.  Having them installed in nova-compute is confusing at best.
Also a failure to install syslinux would lead to no pxelinux.0 in the
tftpd root due to the copy code path failing open.

Change-Id: Ib51383c495fbe00626e45328cea7b7dd5d7bb0d0

commit_message:
Install qemu-utils with nova-compute.

The split out of nova-kvm and nova-baremetal was buggy: qemu-utils is
needed to deploy baremetal images, so we should install it for every
nova-compute install. Similarly syslinux contains pxelinux.0 for
nova-baremetal as well as whatever nova-kvm uses from it.

Change-Id: I24eba7ecc3ca4eb9987b18693342d7a5ac2c8dee

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-06-27 02:29:33.000000000', 'message': 'Ports depend on the subnets in the same network.

Without establishing this implicit dependency, the following
sometimes occurs:
- Ports get assigned to instances without any IP address
- Stack delete fails as ports still exist in subnets.

Fixes bug: #1192371

Change-Id: Ifd892cef4c2eebaea5568afbd320c8865c845d70
'}]
commit_message:
Ports depend on the subnets in the same network.

Without establishing this implicit dependency, the following
sometimes occurs:
- Ports get assigned to instances without any IP address
- Stack delete fails as ports still exist in subnets.

Fixes bug: #1192371

Change-Id: Ifd892cef4c2eebaea5568afbd320c8865c845d70

commit_message:
add missing gettextutils imports

Several files use the "_" function, but don't import it from
gettextutils - this leads to a "NameError: name '_' is not
defined" error if you try to import/use the modules from an
interactive python shell or standalone test-code.

Change-Id: Id28b45d71eeda64fbfaa6234b12cff45fcd2ce40

commit_message:
Jointly load ExternalNetwork with Network

Bug 1177572

This patch leverages the same approach as bug 1174111 for avoiding
loading ExternalNetwork element from db for each network element.
make_network_dict, _extend_network_dict_l3 are refactored accordingly.

Also, this patch sligthly alters the logic of process_l3_network_create
and process_l3_network_update as these methods assumed
_extend_network_dict_l3 was always executed before retuerning.

Finally, calls to get_network and get_networks in plugins which only
extended the response with l3 attributes have been completely removed.

Change-Id: I3b4c28ec0c78f731a534c2b66150d529fd797e72

Break out Compute Manager unit tests

As we convert things to objects, it'll be easier to convert our compute
Manager tests to be true unit tests if they are in their own class.

There are currently a handful of tests that are true unit tests and
require no DB access.  These are now moved, subclassing from
test.NoDBTestCase.

Related to blueprint unified-object-model

commit_message:
Break out compute API unit tests

As we convert things to objects, it'll be easier to convert our compute
API tests to be true unit tests if they are in their own class.  This
also allows us to move away from the hacks needed to simulate 2 DBs in
order to test ComputeCellsAPI().

There are currently a handful of tests that are true unit tests and
require no DB access.  These are now moved, subclassing from
test.NoDBTestCase.

Related to blueprint unified-object-model

Change-Id: I72f4f6ada8d0586e813e551a1b361bcebb16ee66

commit_message:
Expose resource dependency required_by to REST API.

Each resource can generate a list of names of resources which
require this resource as a direct (non transitive) dependency.

This information is returned in the list as well as the show REST calls
so that a diagram of the running stack can be built with a single
request.

Other uses of exposing this information is:
- template authors debugging their own template dependency issues
- integration tests validating template dependencies

Change-Id: Ibe62345afa87e49c4e2152a5fcb74e5ee003124e

commit_message:
Fix index link in footer bar

bug 1192692

Sphinx isn't configured to load the tempest modules,
so the easiest fix is to remove the links to the
general and module indices (which don't exist).

Fix volume info display error on create with v2.

Error due to popping 'links' when it does not exist.

Fixes: bug 1190853

commit_message:
CoraidDriver: Create_volume_from_snapshot of a different size

When you create a Volume from a Snapshot, the 'size' argument for the
new volume isn't used at all.
So, the new volume created will be created (successfully but) with the
same size as the snapshot size.

Cinder think the volume has been created with the right size.

We just need to call Coraid ESM LV Resize with the REST API after
the volume has been created.

Fixes bug 1158959

Change-Id: I760fe1ba4052bb2d5b1a1a5c55c9a976522af107

[{'created': '2013-07-01 03:32:20.000000000', 'message': 'Move tests into project package.

There are several reasons for this. One is that the majority of
OpenStack packages behave this way. The second is that it makes writing
software that extends something easier to test (which is a clear usecase
for openstackclient) And third, tests/__init__.py implies a global
package named "tests" - which I'm pretty sure we're not providing.

Change-Id: Ic708ffd92aea78c2ffc1a8579af0587af4fca4ff
'}]
commit_message:
Move tests into project package.

There are several reasons for this. One is that the majority of
OpenStack packages behave this way. The second is that it makes writing
software that extends something easier to test (which is a clear usecase
for openstackclient) And third, tests/__init__.py implies a global
package named "tests" - which I'm pretty sure we're not providing.

Change-Id: Ic708ffd92aea78c2ffc1a8579af0587af4fca4ff

[{'created': '2013-06-28 06:35:25.000000000', 'message': "Add python-libguestfs to RPM list

libguestfs appears to be the best way to access images for injection,
so add the python bindings to the RPM list.  Indeed, on RHEL it is the
only way, because the fallback of nbd access isn't available.  There,
this change prevents a lot of errors in nova.virt.disk.vfs.localfs

Change-Id: I9c2a81bb7c26bc17f8b5f1b5a682c05a419b33ba

commit_message:
Add python-libguestfs to RPM list

libguestfs appears to be the best way to access images for injection,
so add the python bindings to the RPM list.  Indeed, on RHEL it is the
only way, because the fallback of nbd access isn't available.  There,
this change prevents a lot of errors in nova.virt.disk.vfs.localfs
when it can't import the nbd module.

Change-Id: I9c2a81bb7c26bc17f8b5f1b5a682c05a419b33ba

messages:
[{'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-05-17 05:48:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Very cool, looks a lot like the taskflow library that  is being built. Should fit in very nicely :-)'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-05-17 19:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think this makes sense. I was thinking about something similar in:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/29077/

I am not so fussed about using inheritance, I would rather we 'refactored' the code into two "duck similar" task classes, then look at what is common once we have them both in the conductor. The only draw back is we probably have to create, then almost immediately ditch, a whole bunch of rpc methods.

Would be interested in what you think? I am good with trying something else though. Just wondering what you were thinking?'}, {'account_id': 4601, 'date': '2013-05-17 19:31:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

We will probably have things in common that will worth to put in a common class, like those examples, 'execute' and 'get_destination_host' as well as the rpc objects instances so I think it does not hurt putting then even before we refactor both tasks.

By the way, I got that from your patch and I just forgot to add you as a reviewer.

I was thinking to add that structure in advance to facilitate things since we will touch on the same files and common stuffs."}, {'account_id': 4601, 'date': '2013-05-20 13:58:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-05-21 14:01:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hmm, I don't really see the point in breaking things out like this, and it seems too heavyweight, at least at this point.

Can you give us some more detail about what you hope to accomplish with this approach?"}, {'account_id': 4601, 'date': '2013-05-21 14:51:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ok. We have a bunch of helper functions and other stuffs that would be nice to get them separated and isolated out from conductor manager for clearness. My idea is to add, prior the other big changes, a new structure that will hold the migration stuffs separated by 'type'. I used 'tasks' as suggested by John.
Regarding the inheritance... we will have things in common for sure and I thought we could create the skeleton that way to minimize repeating code. But yeah, it can be heavyweight for now."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-05-22 10:58:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I am +1 for dropping the inheritance for now. A set of common utils and a single code path seem more likely as an end point.

For example, in the XenAPI code I want to move resize to have the move disk be a live-migrate operation, hopefully soonish.

I think the separation from conductor manager made more sense before the Compute API split that Russel just did. Maybe we should just add stuff into there for now."}, {'account_id': 4601, 'date': '2013-05-22 12:42:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Lets hold this change for now until we get other stuffs finally defined.'}]

Add common crypto utilties

Common routines for Key Derivation (RFC 5869) and Symmetric Cryptography
that uses standard Crypto functions as exported by PyCrypto

Change-Id: Ib43ac788ec98b8a1b678ac457244a06a16833761
Implements: blueprint trusted-messaging

See bug #1194807

Neutron and oslo-incubator already uses oslo.config 1.2.0a2. Nova used

commit_message:
Allow use of oslo.config-1.2.0a3

See bug #1194807

Neutron and oslo-incubator already uses oslo.config 1.2.0a2. Nova used
it briefly but we hit an issue.

1.2.0a3 contains a fix for a regression in the registration of the oslo
namespace package, so it doesn't make sense to allow a2.

Change-Id: Ib054c2a1edaf39507c8faf7d03aadb00eb57ca79

[{'created': '2013-07-02 10:49:16.000000000', 'message': "Overhaul quantum networking for non-seed clouds.

depended on two network interfaces, forced NAT that we don't need and

* New definitions for the meaning of various config keys to suit
  working with different cloud layers.

commit_message:
Overhaul quantum networking for non-seed clouds.

The networking setup was inappropriate for non-seed clouds - it
depended on two network interfaces, forced NAT that we don't need and
could not be turned off. Additionally there wasn't much clarity
between idempotent machine config and non-idempotent service config.

Key changes in this patch:
* No longer write persistent device files, instead update
  idempotently.
* NAT rules are now setup idempotently on each o-r-c run.
* New definitions for the meaning of various config keys to suit
  working with different cloud layers.

Change-Id: Ie86be0fc884b4c4f655d73da345bdee45fcde473

add tests - list servers using admin user

user, parameter 'all_tenants' is required.

commit_message:
api : Add actions resume support

Add support for resume action using a similar interface to that provided
by nova for the admin actions extension.  So a body of {'resume': None}
will suspend the stack, see http://api.openstack.org/api-ref.html

Change-Id: I89bbafbe2f8b2503f241659a36b83ceab605e763
blueprint: stack-suspend-resume

commit_message:
Fix return error when resource can't be found

By current implement, the HTTP request for /v2/resources/<resource_id>
will return 500 if there is no coresponding resource or the resource id
is invalid. And the response is as below:

{"error_message": "{"debuginfo": null, "faultcode": "Server",
"faultstring": "list index out of range"}"}

After fixed, the response will be like this:

{"error_message": "{"debuginfo": null, "faultcode": "Client",
"faultstring": "Invalid input for field/attribute resource_id.
Value: '9'. Unknown resource"}"}

Fixes bug: 1195925

Change-Id: I73c73fb3ba57bc6cbbf421f9ac5ec3cdb68ce784

commit_message:
Several minor changes

 * Base image name and keypair name were added to cluster details
 * In Node Group Details renamed fields: 'Node Group' to 'Name', 'Nodes Count'
   to 'Number of Nodes', 'Node Group Template' to 'Template'.
 * In cluster details instances now have http links

Change-Id: Ie582228c4956145a222f7021658c538ca1c7b80a

Enable environment passing for chaining filters

Combine environment setting from both the chaining
filter as well as the leaf filter that was chained
when get_environment() is called. Add testcase.

Change-Id: I908552a38e14cb20eae67b4a9f381f50ef87c5e5

commit_message:
Decouple boot-stack from non-Heat configuration.

At the moment boot-stack assumes it is being booted without Heat or
any other cloud infrastructure. This is only correct for the seed node
- everything after that is booted into an environment with working
Heat, Neutron etc.

By splitting it out we make boot-stack more suitable for bootstrapping
the undercloud and overcloud clouds.

Change-Id: I6051da5ee708b866d90e095c51e105da919bfeef

commit_message:
Handle ECONNREFUSED exception in SolidFire driver.

The SolidFire driver wasn't handling connection exceptions
during init (capacity updates from scheduler).

This patch add a try/except wrap around the two places
that this is called and logs and error rather than crashing
cinder-volume service.

Fixes bug: 1195910

Change-Id: I30347cc0973bbf9dbc30ea02e204560095fc75b4

commit_message:
Update kombu requirement

The minimum version of kombu in the requirements
list has been updated to ensure that compatible
kombu and msgpack libraries are used across all
projects. This update also requires a bump to
anyjson.

Addresses bug #1134575

Change-Id: Idf29f4cb510d87a82ea1ff0ffda2e094ace9f2e6
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug.hellmann@dreamhost.com>

commit_message:
Fix MGMT api failures due to Nova api change

Nova packages clients with `hosts` instead of `rdhosts`. This
patch updates the models and views related to hosts so that
they match the specifications given in the Nova api templates.

Change-Id: Ib438d279b7886659a095f112a421990d6d35b2d6
Fixes: bug #1130983

(1 inline comment)

Hey Jeremiah,

Thanks a lot for this patch, your work and your thoughts.

Unfortunately, I don't think multipart-form is something we want / need in Glance. As for now, there are several ways to work around your issue with browsers, but I guess the most common are:

1) Use API v2
2) Handle multipart in your application and pipe the request / data to glanceclient. (Just as horizon does)


The patch adds more code to Glance that will have to be maintained, debugged and that has a single use case, glance wise. 

Again, thanks for the contribution. I hope the above makes sense to you."}, {'account_id': 6499, 'date': '2013-06-14 13:52:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

There are more multiple ways to support upload. Using multipart-for-mdata should be allowed. I am not sure why the strong objection to the code. The code has been tested and debugged and has been maintained at HP, it is being used in production. In addition, the blueprint has been approved for havana.

Thanks for you consideration.

-Yehia'}, {'account_id': 7767, 'date': '2013-06-14 21:09:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

David and Flavio,

   Thanks for taking the time to review the changes.

I will try to address your comments/concerns below:

Concern 1) Why not v2?
We did look at v2, however, for submitting from a browser, there are still some problems.  I do think moving away from the use of headers to submit the metadata is good.  However, the id of the upload still needs to be put in the headers for the actual POST.  For IE this is a non-starter without the ability to do multipart forms.  

Concern 2) Why not do what dashboard does - provide a separate way to do uploading to the actual server and do the add locally?
I considered this as an option, but the solution was lacking in my opinion for a couple of reasons.  First, it seems to leave glance incomplete in my opinion.  My opinion is that glance should be designed to handle image uploading in a robust fashion - why should adopters of glance have to reinvent the wheel to push their images because glance's solution, while improved in v2, is still not terribly robust or functional beyond simple raw access through curl (in my opinion).  Second, if we decide at some point to move glance to its own node for our needs, for example, we no longer have our application in tandem with glance - leaving us with the need again to cobble another solution.

Concern 3) This is just another path to support so this change doubles the support ("sound like dual maintenance for no reason")

Actually, the change was designed to participate as much as possible with the code that was already there.  Most of the work is in the util changes or the deserializer to keep the code separate and easy to maintain.  The work to ensure that the actual payload looked like a file was to keep inline with the way glance does a straight binary payload POST.  Any maintenance of the way glance itself works should work for both straight binary dumps and multipart form dumps.

At the end of the day, browser uploads are bad news, and difficult to support (pre HTML5 anyway), but we won't be expecting our customers to issue curl commands to push their images either.  v2 moves towards a better answer, but still doesn't seem to address things like recovery from com/client/server failures resulting in a restart of the transfer and the ability to resend parts of the transfer (relying on http's idea of chunking the data).  Maybe that's ok, but it seems to me to be a hindrance for wider adoption.'}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-06-14 22:31:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Yehia,

The particular implementation is quite invasive and looks like a support/refactoring burden moving forward, for a feature that doesn't resonate with many of us. I originally approved the blueprint thinking that it would not be quite so invasive.


Jeremiah,

Thanks for your submission! I'm sorry to say that glance api v1 is enough of a mess that there isn't an easy or clean way to make the change to multipart form data. 

Can you go into more detail about "However, the id of the upload still needs to be put in the headers for the actual POST. For IE this is a non-starter without the ability to do multipart forms." I'm not sure I understand, and it would be very interesting to phrase this feature as a v2 feature request.

As a separate suggestion, do you think it would be possible to implement multipart form support in a wsgi middleware that translates the content type from multipart form data to what glance v1 api currently expects? I think a middleware might be a good way to minimize the impact of this change.


Thanks guys.'}, {'account_id': 7767, 'date': '2013-06-17 15:15:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The analysis I made for v2 was incorrect - when I had read it before, I thought that the PUT for the image required that the image id be passed in the headers - I could swear that's what I saw - I was looking at a draft of the spec and not the spec itself, but I may have just read it wrong too.

Anyway, the id for the image is passed in the URL, so all is well there, the content type is the only header required, so my original "non-starter" comment is invalid.

As far as making the change in the middleware, technically, it is doable - my question is, are you sure you would want to do that?  Multipart forms are a generic construct and can encode any mime-type and can encode multiple files. 

Granted, the implementation I submitted doesn't take this into account, but pushing it down to Glance's wsgi layer would either mean many kinds of multipart forms would not work correctly, or implementing a more generic multipart form translation where, for example, multiple files would each be their own "POST" (for v1) - i.e., one request would generate several to the daemon code.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 5313, 'date': '2013-06-24 15:38:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The move to implement this in v2 sounds right to me, we probably need to also figure out what will it take for nova to start using v2 client, that way things will flow better, you are probably still in v1 because nova has not moved to v2. I think overall we need to figure out why nova has not moved and help, this will simplify this dual maintenance of glance API versions.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-02 06:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-07-02 06:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

[{'created': '2013-06-11 22:49:25.000000000', 'message': 'blueprint support-for-multipart-form-data-contenttype

Changes the upload path to handle form content versus a straight
file post as well as size (some browsers won't push the size of the
file, and it wouldn't match the content-length because the form data
contains more than the file contents).

A util was added to parse out the form parts into "headers" as they
would be in a regular POST.

The deserializer was modified to co-opt the deserialization code path
if there is a multipart form submittal otherwise it puts the daemon
back on the old deserialize path

the cgi.FieldStorage will leak file handles (that you can't see because
FieldStorage unlinks them) without a change to the
implementation of FieldStorage (i.e., via monkey patch - or changes to
wsgi/webob) this should be filed as a bug and the community should decide
what to do.  The monkey patch is very simple....here's the proposed code:

def create_FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch(dir=None):
    """
    Generates a function to monkey patch FieldStorage's make_file
    with one that's a bit more flexible.
    """
    def FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch(self, binary=False):
        """
        Creates a tempfile in a predefined
        """
        if dir != None:
            t = tempfile.TemporaryFile("w+b", dir=dir)
        else:
            t = tempfile.TemporaryFile("w+b")

        return t

    return FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch

Then add the following lines in __init__ for the api controller

        #Monkey Patch cgi.FieldStorage.make_file
        cgi.FieldStorage.__dict__['make_file'] = \
            create_FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch(
                self.conf.temp_upload_dir )

Change-Id: Idd34336f59acbeaeb6f91c7f147a72c8e538d77e

commit_message:
blueprint support-for-multipart-form-data-contenttype

Changes the upload path to handle form content versus a straight
file post as well as size (some browsers won't push the size of the
file, and it wouldn't match the content-length because the form data
contains more than the file contents).

A util was added to parse out the form parts into "headers" as they
would be in a regular POST.

The deserializer was modified to co-opt the deserialization code path
if there is a multipart form submittal otherwise it puts the daemon
back on the old deserialize path

The size in the content length header is adjusted for form submittals
size the actual content length is greater than the image size.  Because
some browsers are not cooperative around reporting sizes, the code was
made to go through a series of heuristics to devine the size of the image
passed across the network.

the cgi.FieldStorage will leak file handles (that you can't see because
FieldStorage unlinks them) without a change to the
implementation of FieldStorage (i.e., via monkey patch - or changes to
wsgi/webob) this should be filed as a bug and the community should decide
what to do.  The monkey patch is very simple....here's the proposed code:

def create_FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch(dir=None):
    """
    Generates a function to monkey patch FieldStorage's make_file
    with one that's a bit more flexible.
    """
    def FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch(self, binary=False):
        """
        Creates a tempfile in a predefined
        """
        if dir != None:
            t = tempfile.TemporaryFile("w+b", dir=dir)
        else:
            t = tempfile.TemporaryFile("w+b")

        return t

    return FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch

Then add the following lines in __init__ for the api controller

        #Monkey Patch cgi.FieldStorage.make_file
        cgi.FieldStorage.__dict__['make_file'] = \
            create_FieldStorage_make_file_monkey_patch(
                self.conf.temp_upload_dir )

Change-Id: Idd34336f59acbeaeb6f91c7f147a72c8e538d77e

commit_message:
Make novaclient CLI extendable

Fix bug 1192855

Now we can add new OpenStack CLI by creating some .py files in
python-novaclient/novaclient/v1_1/contrib but this is not extendable,
if create some folders under novaclient/v1_1/contrib, then the files
in these folders cannot be retrieved by novaclient.

For example, some contributes might want to create their own CLIs
in python-novaclient/novaclient/v1_1/contrib/contributor1/*.py and
those files will not be recognized by novaclient.

The fix was use os.walk() to retrive all folders/files under
novaclient/v1_1/contrib to make sure all files can be loaded.

Change-Id: I51c0cbcdc50a296c56a5a51e322d08370e36cc14

commit_message:
Document the OVS restart for the Ryu agent

When installing Quantum Ryu agent, the OVS service might not be properly
started due to a missing kernel module (compiled using DKMS). Make sure
that the OVS service is (re)started before restarting the Ryu agent
(completes commit 9489e66).

Cherry-picked from https://review.openstack.org/34230

Change-Id: I659415bb7514cf5ac3619141e715351692c80854

[{'created': '2013-06-25 22:53:23.000000000', 'message': 'Removes 3PAR domain option from cinder config file

The HP 3PAR domain is no longer required to be specified in the
cinder configuration file. This patch automatically looks up the
domain using the Common Provisioning Group (CPG) specified.

Change-Id: I3ed01eed26209caa1904bec1f585059860294f38
Fixes: bug 1194599
'}, {'created': '2013-06-26 15:42:32.000000000', 'message': 'Removes 3PAR domain option from cinder config file

The HP 3PAR domain is no longer required to be specified in the
cinder configuration file. This patch automatically looks up the
domain using the Common Provisioning Group (CPG) specified.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3ed01eed26209caa1904bec1f585059860294f38
Fixes: bug 1194599
'}, {'created': '2013-06-27 22:54:13.000000000', 'message': 'Removes 3PAR domain option from cinder config file

The HP 3PAR domain is no longer required to be specified in the
cinder configuration file. This patch automatically looks up the
domain using the Common Provisioning Group (CPG) specified.
hp3par_domain will remain in the config for now and will be
logged as deprecated. It will be removed in the I release.

DocImpact

commit_message:
Removes 3PAR domain option from cinder config file

The HP 3PAR domain is no longer required to be specified in the
cinder configuration file. This patch automatically looks up the
domain using the Common Provisioning Group (CPG) specified.
hp3par_domain will remain in the config for now and will be
logged as deprecated. It will be removed in the I release.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3ed01eed26209caa1904bec1f585059860294f38
Fixes: bug 1194599

of alarms (i.e. with trivial global partitioning).

Beautifully written! One question tho', will the notifying and alarm transition be totally decoupled? So once in the alarm state will we keep getting alarm notifications - I hope so? We had a bug in heat recently where autoscaling stopped scaling if the new server was also working hard (i.e. it kept the alarm in the alarm state and we stopped getting notifications). - I'll +2 when the tests work."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-06-26 08:40:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@asalkeld - I had in mind two styles of notification strategy:

1. one-shot notification for simple best-effort webhooks or for "guaranteed" delivery mechanisms with their own internal retry logic (e.g. email or SMS via Marconi)

2. continuous notification for webhooks that could benefit from repeated reassurance that the triggering condition still hold

I think #2 would address the Heat use-case, though I haven't thought through the details yet as to how this policy would be driven (e.g. could be as simple as an attribute of the alarm actions).

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-06-26 09:16:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-26 09:18:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Doesn't seem to work

Basic alarm threshold evaluation logic.

querying, threshold comparison, and state transition rules.

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-06-27 17:02:06.000000000', 'message': "`tox -ecover` failure. Missing entry in tox.ini

`tox -ecover` is failing due to a missing entry in keystone's tox.ini file.
In tox.ini the following code appears:
'''
[testenv:cover]
setenv = NOSE_WITH_COVERAGE=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML_DIR={toxinidir}/cover
'''

Adding 'VIRTUAL_ENV={envdir}' to the setenv mapping, as shown below,
has resolved the issue on my machine.
'''
[testenv:cover]
setenv = VIRTUAL_ENV={envdir}
         NOSE_WITH_COVERAGE=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML_DIR={toxinidir}/cover
'''

Change-Id: I3550ac61cdc6389dd239c5ad319d881519b3543d
Fixes: bug #1195371
"}]
commit_message:
`tox -ecover` failure. Missing entry in tox.ini

`tox -ecover` is failing due to a missing entry in keystone's tox.ini file.
In tox.ini the following code appears:
'''
[testenv:cover]
setenv = NOSE_WITH_COVERAGE=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML_DIR={toxinidir}/cover
'''

Adding 'VIRTUAL_ENV={envdir}' to the setenv mapping, as shown below,
has resolved the issue on my machine.
'''
[testenv:cover]
setenv = VIRTUAL_ENV={envdir}
         NOSE_WITH_COVERAGE=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML=1
         NOSE_COVER_HTML_DIR={toxinidir}/cover
'''

Change-Id: I3550ac61cdc6389dd239c5ad319d881519b3543d
Fixes: bug #1195371

commit_message:
Added Cinder volume backup to Ceph support

Added new Ceph backup service to allow backup
of Cinder volumes to a Ceph object store. This
driver is compatible with the existing backup
interface provided by the Swift backup service.

Implements: blueprint cinder-backup-to-ceph

Change-Id: I299f033347cb263e7169c4a4efb758d19e753f46

commit_message:
Session cleanup for db.security_group_* methods

Remove session parameter from:

 security_group_get
 security_group_get_by_name
 security_group_create
 security_group_update
 security_group_ensure_default

security_group_count_by_project left as is as
it involves quota changes and will be done separately
with other _count_by_project functions.

Convert security_group_destroy to use model_query() instead
of session.query().

blueprint db-session-cleanup

Change-Id: I31e8333f67cf900b6f4aa6c5b967a9a6fb71147e

commit_message:
Document how to manually simulate infrastructure.

Fixes bug 1172428.

* README.rst: Developers often have a need to recreate gating
integration tests manually, and this provides a walkthrough of
making a DG-slave-like throwaway server without the overhead of
building other CI infrastructure to manage a pool of them. This can
be useful to reproduce and troubleshoot failures or tease out
nondeterministic bugs. The driving use case is for pre-testing
embargoed vulnerability fixes, increasing the chance they can get
through gating on the first try.

Change-Id: I0f78011c183f64b894b336eb8e0d25dc5ba00bde

commit_message:
Quantumapi returns an empty network list

When nova retries network list and if the list is empty, quantumapi
should return a empty list instead of an empty dictionnary.

Fixes bug 1189976

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/network/test_quantumv2.py

Change-Id: I5b8c498a6c86e92d0de14d8de9e55722408c5669
(cherry picked from commit 14d3ae58c1ec39edd1b0b2a2a1947c5f8e96bab5)

While I'm OK with the general idea behind this, I've stepped through this code before trying to pin down a tempest failure and I was at least happy that it doesn't return at random places in such a big block of code.  So rather than simply return in the middle of the method, I'd like to see that checks for len(nets) before the for loop over security groups (which would fix your bug) and then everything else should fall through, right?  Then we have a single exit point in the method (unless an exception is raised).

Otherwise if you are going to leave this as-is, I think you should at least have a log statement (warning?) in that block that says no networks were found (rather than silently returning). I've had a hell of a time in here before in part because of the lack of logging as it goes through such a big block of code (note I was testing with a quantum backend)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-24 19:49:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Skip security group code when there is no network.

This patch adds a simple check to the nova/quantum API that immediately
returns an empty list if there are no configured networks available.

Fixes bug 1191044

Change-Id: I34ac4dd56c71f99c7ed9ff632d6dc7036d91008d

commit_message:
Handle UnexpectedTaskState and InstanceNotFound exceptions

UnexpectedTaskState and InstanceNotFound are thrown when a delete
of the instance happens before the ongoing action is completed.
These are to be handled gracefully.
These exceptions have to be logged and not reraised, as they are false
alarms.

Fixes: bug #1186447

Change-Id: I0647935c4452d4294f49a4c0d08e480584ebec7c

commit_message:
Optimize SecurityGroupsOutputController by len(servers)

The following patch adds an optimization for _extend_servers() so that
it calls get_instance_security_groups() when len(servers) == 1, and
get_instances_security_groups_bindings() when > 1. In addition, this patch
adds a return statement if not len(servers) as there is no reason to
perform a query if there are no servers.

Fixes bug 1182730

Change-Id: I149bf32176d60e72d76576168d15995f7215b657
(cherry picked from commit 604e77654d0c7eb5fda9600e9ca604da656d856)
